column9: Covered in sugar and only 250mg per serving
column10: We are seniors and are taking Vitamin D3, C, and Zinc which are the three essentials determined by the health officials to strengthen your immune system against Covid-19. Seniors such as ourselves are prone to have a greater reaction to the disease. For vitamin C, it was determined to take 2,000mg a day, or two tablets a day at 1,000mg a day. First complaint is that these gummies are only 250mg of Vitamin C. You'd have to take 8 a day to get 2,000mg of Vitamin C.Second complaint is that I'm pre-diabetic, and the gummies are covered with sugar. I really wish that we could have gotten these at 1,000mg and NO SUGAR on the gummies. Naturemade adheres to USP standards, which a lot of supplement companies don't do. But taking 250mg of Vitamin C is not sufficient, and a lot of pre- or diabetics will have a small spike in sugar even if it's a small one-- eating these gummies. I hope they work this out. Until then, we've found a gel capsule filled with 1,00mg solid vitamin C. I know gummies are more absorb-able. More supplement companies need to step up their game, and make them healthier and stronger.

column9: I can literally feel the quality of this Vitamin C!
column10: I bought this brand from another seller and didn't get the original product as listed.  This product however is the real deal!I also tried a totally different brand that was very expensive and didn't work at all.  I am very sensitive to when I'm lacking in vitaminC.  My gums itch/ache and my joints hurt.  I came back to the Kirkland brand and within a few days, my symptoms resolved.  I take one in the morning and at night.  If I'm catching a cold or trying to boost my immune system, I take 3-4 a day.  Your tolerance may be different.  There are 500 tablets in each jar.  After opening and closing over and over the air may oxidize the tablets. To avoid this - I only take out what I need in a month and keep in a sealed jar in the refrigerator. I also keep the original bottle tightly closed in the fridge. VitaminC products of any kind don't like warm, or humid storage.  The fridge is your best bet!I've taken these without food and don't have any stomach discomfort.  They are chewable and pleasant in taste.  Best Vitamin C out there!

column9: Great but you only need one per day
column10: There is a lot of misinformation about vitamin C out there, people encourage others to take thousands of milligrams a day of vitamin C but the vast majority of that is wasted.  Vitamin C absorption relies on an enzyme, we only produce enough of that enzyme to absorb 300-400 MG of vitamin C per day.  Several independent studies found plasma saturation occurs between 300 and 400 MG of oral Vitamin C per day, all you really need is a 500 MG supplement though a 1000 wont be harmful.  Once plasma saturation occurs any additional Vitamin C is excreted through urine and NOT used by the body.  The only way to absorb more than 300-400 MG per day is IV administration.  I wouldn't go the IV route, the human body has a limit to absorption for a reason and forcing more into your body after that is likely to cause unanticipated side effects.

column9: C-1000 COMPLEX vs regular. Also, Do Not Cut In Half!
column10: This is a great and well priced product. When I start feeling the onset of a cold, I just pop one of this and I am normally able to recover in half a day or so. It also doesn't give me upset stomach since it's buffered.** Make Sure You Are Getting the C-1000 Complex, and not the C-1000 **The Amazon listing titles for these two products are somewhat confusing.  The NOW C-1000 COMPLEX cost a couple dollars more but is buffered - i.e. less likely to cause stomach problem.Here's the description from NOW's web site about the "Buffer" feature: "Calcium Ascorbate is not acidic and will not contribute to excess stomach acidity or irritation in sensitive persons.  Calcium Ascorbate is synthesized from a combination of Ascorbic Acid and Calcium Carbonate to form Calcium Ascorbate."Also, some people would buy this, and then cut it in half, thinking that it's a better deal to buy the 1000mg pills. However, this will reduce or nullify the effect of the "sustain release". Moreover, there is no guarantee that the ingredients are equally divided between the two halfs. Unless the manufacturer put a "cut line" in the middle of the pill, it's a pretty good bet that the pill is not intended to be cut in half because the ingredients are probably not equally distributed within the one pill.For comparison shopping, since Amazon doesn't list the content, here is the Supplement Info for the C-1000 COMPLEX:Serving Size: 1 CapsuleAmount Per Serving:Vitamin C (from Calcium Ascorbate) 1.0 g (1,000 mg)  1667%Calcium (from Calcium Ascorbate) 110 mg  11%Citrus Bioflavonoids (37% total bioflavonoids as Hesperidin) 500 mgAcerola  50 mgRutin  50 mgOther Ingredients: Calcium Phosphate, Cellulose, Stearic Acid (vegetable source), Croscarmellose Sodium, Magnesium Stearate (vegetable source), Silica and Vegetable Coating.

column9: High dose multivitamins with added sugar and bovine gelatine!
column10: Emergen-C's "Energy Release and Immunity Support" food supplement is a high dose (1000mg) Vitamin C (Ascorbic acid) plus multi-vitamin and mineral product. It is supplied in boxes of single-dose sachets of powder which rapidly dissolves in water to produce an orange-flavoured daily health drink, designed to give you a daily energy and vitamin boost.The product offers a dose of vitamins well in excess of the recommended daily amounts (Vitamins: C - 1250%; B1 - 136%; B2 - 121%; B6 - 429%; B12 - 720%; D - 200%) as well as fair top-up of minerals Potassium, Calcium, Magnesium, Manganese, Chromium and Zinc (the Calcium and Zinc being particularly important as mineral accompaniments to Ascorbic acid). It is flavoured with natural orange and lemon extract and coloured with additional E162 (Betanin, aka Beetroot Red) natural food dye. So far, so good.Where the product falls down in the health-giving stakes is in its massive sugar content: it contains large amounts of fructose, cane sugar and maltodextrin as sweeteners -- which explains the product's "energy boosting" claims. It also contains bovine gelatine as an entirely superfluous ingredient which immediately renders it unsuitable for vegetarians or vegans.  Be aware too that some people suffer reactions to Ascorbic acid in the form of swelling to the face, water retention or digestive disorders; no warnings about these potential (but uncommon) side effects are given on the packaging of this product.For those wanting a short-term high dose blast of Vitamin C and a general immune system boost to face down an impending winter cold, these powders are probably OK. To avoid the sugar they contain, though, it is probably better to opt for "     Redoxon Double Action                       " effervescent tablets instead, especially as these also offer a higher Zinc content (although these use Aspartame as the sweetener instead, which comes with its own problems). They do lack the additional vitamins, but it's probably also better to tailor vitamin and mineral supplementation to your diet and lifestyle than to take a single multi-mix. You might also wish to bear in mind that unless your immune system is taking a hit owing to an underlying health issue, it is generally regarded as undesirable to take regular large doses of Vitamin C over prolonged periods; they should be avoided altogether by anyone suffering from renal problems.

column9: Easy to Use Vitamin C Packs
column10: EmergenC + Zinc (just before the onset of a cold) = less severe cold. That's the conclusion I've come to after my non-scientific years of using both of these ingredients.Someone told me about this tip years ago, and ever since I started using      Zicam Cold Remedy Rapid Melts                        and Emergen-C—right as I sensed a cold was developing, my colds didn't last more than a day and weren't as severe.— PREVENT A COLD —When I say, "right before a cold," I mean that weird feeling in the back of your nose/throat (pay attention the next time it happens). When you get that feeling, start taking Zicam every 4-5 hours, along with one pack of EmergenC a day, and drink lots of water. Repeat this for two days tops. Once your cold hits, stop taking Zicam, and only the EmergenC and lots of water. If you should get a fever, take some Advil. I have done this for every cold for the past five years and my colds have not been bad at all. There were times that I didn't take Zicam in time and the colds were bad.That's my experience with EmergenC. Take what you will from that, but don't consider it professional medical advice. column9: Formula contains aspartic acid , not safe .
column10: I have been taking this formerly wonderful health aid for over a decade .Not knowing when it was added or if it had always been there, aspartic acid. . I have always recommended this to everyone that I know/knew. not anymore .I quote bekow in paranthesis from: (...)"The aspartic acid in Emergen-C can create a similar reaction to the aspartic acid in aspartame.Emergen-C® helps promote immune health, especially used as a prevention during cold and flu season. Each individual packet is a delicious fizzy drink mix that delivers 1,000 mg of vitamin C as ascorbic acid, as well as 24 nutrients with antioxidants, electrolytes and 7 B vitamins.I am not saying that Emergen-C is not a good product, but I can’t use it, unfortunately, and if you have ever had a reaction to the aspartic acid in aspartame, you may have a similar reaction to the aspartic acid in Emergen-C, like I did..Isolated aspartic acid can create blinding eye reactions.Aspartame is 40 percent aspartic acid, and I experienced severe vision reactions to it. After drinking a diet cola, I would develop bright squiggly lines in my line of vision, and the lines would grow to the point that I was temporarily blinded. Then, the bright light would disappear into my head and leave me with a screaming migraine.Once I realized that the aspartame in sugar-free diet colas was the source of this, I removed all aspartame from my life, and I never experienced another one of the squiggly line/migraine episodes. Until I started using Emergen-C, that is.Several months after my recovery from aspartame poisoning, I adopted a stellar wellness program. I was taking around 4,000 mg of ascorbic acid every day, and my friend who owned the local health food store suggested that I try the Emergen-C, which has 1,000 mg ascorbic acid in each packet.Gladly, I tried it, and bam – the bright, squiggly lines and migraines started up again. The migraines were not as bad as those caused by aspartame, but the squiggly lines were blinding.I went on the hunt to figure out what I had gotten into. I was disappointed to learn that it was the aspartic acid in the Emergen-C.Research shows that isolated aspartic acid can result in severe headaches.The research shows that isolated aspartic acid can negatively affect the brain and central nervous system. Well, I knew that was right!Aspartic acid, also known as aspartate, is considered a non-essential amino acid, which can be synthesized within the body. The problem comes from isolating the amino acid – this can be dangerous to your health.When I was researching aspartame toxicity for my book, 'Sweet Poison', I learned from the researchers that isolated amino acids (like the two found in aspartame) are loose cannons in the brain.Amino acids are supposed to remain in combination, as they are in nature. When amino acids are separated (isolated) in the lab, they lose their natural ability to work in synchronicity; one with the other, and can no longer “balance” one another out. Hence, they can become damaging to the brain, and toxic to the nervous system."I am not the girl who cries wolf at all and did my research after first reading another amazon poster claiming this.

I also added this to my subscribe and save, so I get even more savings.I am a vegetarian and use this to get my B vitamins, which are particularly hard for vegetarians to get without supplementing.  I prefer the powder form as it is more readily absorbed.Super Orange is my favorite flavor; the others are too sweet for me.  I like to briefly warm about 6 oz of water and then add my 1-2 packs.  I feel that it dissolves better in slightly warm water.Vitamin C and B vitamins are water soluble.  If you ingest more than you need, you will just pee them out.  Although excessive Vitamin C can cause diarrhea, so be alert to that.  If you notice your pee is a bright yellow, you probably have taken in more B12 than you need.  This never happens to me so I know 1-2 packs per day is suitable for my needs.  In the past when I drank Red Bull, my pee would be a neon yellow, and fairly rapidly.  Interestingly, Red Bull provides 80% of your RDI for B12, while this product contains 417% leading me to suspect that the form of B12 in Red Bull is not readily absorbed.I have to add (since I am a dietitian and I couldn't write this review in good conscience without doing so) that I do not recommend using Red Bull for your pick-me-up.  I just mentioned it to discuss the quality of the Emergen-C supplement.  But this is not a review for Red Bull, so I'll leave it at that.If you found this review helpful, please feel free to hit "Yes".  Thank you!

column9: Inferior form of Vit C + 2 Teaspoons of Sugar per Serving!?! Yuck.
column10: I started using Emergency-C back when it wasn't in the stores and could only be obtained directly from the manufacturer by ordering online. Back then it used mineral ascorbates in its formula, which is a far superior form of vitamin C. Somewhere along the line they made the switch to the cheaper and inferior ascorbate acid. I also noticed when reading the label today that there are 7 grams of sugar per packet. That's nearly two teaspoons!!! And what is worse the sugar is fructose.  It also contains corn syrup solids. I was informed at a health food store - Amazing as it may sound if you’re hearing this for the first time, vitamins are more than the synthetic fractions we are commonly taught they are. The ascorbic acid you buy at the grocery store every few weeks, thinking you are buying Vitamin C, is just a CHEMICAL copy of naturally occurring ascorbic acid, which itself is still only a fraction of the actual Vitamin C. It is NOT Vitamin C.  Real vitamin C is part of something living, and as such, can impart life. Your synthetic, fractionated chemical ascorbic acid never grew in the ground, never saw the light of day, never was alive or part of anything alive. It’s a CHEMICAL a cornstarch derivative, a sulfuric acid by-product. In your body it’s just another DRUG. Synthetic vitamins have toxic effects from mega-doses and actually can increase the white blood cell count. Vitamins are only necessary in minute quantities on a daily basis. Whole food vitamins, by contrast, are not toxic since the vitamin is complexed in its integral working form, and requires nothing from the body, and triggers no immune response. If you want true vitamin C see a health food store, not a grocery store for Ascorbate. This is true vitamin C, not ascorbic acid.

column9: The one supplement we feel we MUST always have!
column10: My family and I have been using this product consistently now for several years.  Long ago, I believed that the best way to obtain Vitamin C in our diet was through fresh fruit.  Then, in a college chemistry course, we had a lab requiring us to measure the amount of vitamin C in an orange.  I couldn't believe it- there was very little!  I had been spending a lot of money purchasing organic oranges to make my children fresh orange juice, thinking that even though it was terrifically hard on our budget, they were getting this important vitamin.  So, I briefly changed to solid supplements, until we had another lab and found that the binders used in some supplements are so effective at binding, that we couldn't dissolve them with HCl, or even sulfuric acid! Those binders were not going to give up the goods.  I didn't want to try to figure out which brands would actually provide the Vit C and which ones would simply "pass through," so we started using this powdered Emergen-C.  We immediately felt a difference in energy.  First, I'll note that even though the Vitamin C is emphasized, there are more vitamins and minerals in each packet (see photo).  The company sells similar products with variations in content, so if this isn't quite right for you, try looking into those.  The dosage is listed as one packet daily; we each take two as this seems to be the right level for us, though the box warns not to exceed "suggested use." The directions state to mix it into a glass of water.  It dissolves readily with some stirring, without the need to heat it. I am too impatient to dissolve every last bit, so I usually drink down the small amount that didn't dissolve immediately. There is a bit of a "fizz" produced, so if you put it into a water bottle be aware that pressure will increase in a closed system and you may get some spray when you open it up.  The cardboard, glossy box is printed with vegetable-based inks, so when you are finished you can add it to your compost, vermicompost, or mushroom substrate.  The box is cleverly designed so that you can open it two different ways.  If you prefer to store it upright on the smallest side (perhaps to save space), then there is a pull-strip to open it up on the opposite small side, so that becomes the top of the box. The strip includes a tab to insert into the slot underneath so that you can close it again.  All of the envelopes inside are separate packages, so closing it is most helpful if you would happen the box over- it isn't needed to preserve the quality of the product.  There is another option provided to open it. One of the photos shows how it can be opened lengthwise.  On the long side, short edge there is a small arrowhead where it says "push here to open."  You could break a nail trying to do just that, it's best to lift from the nicely perforated curve just below that.  Then, you can open it as far as you want- just a bit to slide one envelope out at a time, crease the top if you want to open it part-way, or remove the whole top along the perforations to expose the 30 packets.  I like to open it all the way for the visual "cue" for my family to use them, just as the fruit & veggie bowl stays out to encourage healthy eating.  Each packet is well-sealed plastic and separately labeled with the ingredients, expiration date and lot number.  On the reverse side there is an orange arrow leading you to the small slit that allows you to easily open the packets without a scissors.  This individual packaging makes it easy to take these along in a purse or backpack, store in a drawer at work, or to slip one into a get-well card when someone who you know is a little under the weather.  I have never had one puncture or leak.  These plastic envelopes do end up in our trash, which I do not like, yet the packaging seems to be the best possible design.  The powder must be kept dry, so using paper envelopes would be risk the product quality and prevent taking these with us.  We separate our doses during the day, so the ability to take it along is important to us.  I suppose if they ever offer some with waxy paper envelopes, we'd use some of each type for home vs. taking on the go. The best value that we have ever found for this product is to include it in our regular subscriptions from Amazon.  We know we're going to use it, so it's convenient to have it show up just when we'd need some more.  If acid bothers your stomach, this product would offer you the option of complete control over the pacing of your dosage.  Otherwise, you'd need a buffered product.  All in all, I'd easily choose this as the only supplement my family and I couldn't live without.

So I received a free sample of Emergen-C from Smiley360, and I was surprised at the effectiveness of one little package. It reminded me a lot of a crumbled Airborne tablet, where you just pour the powder and mix it with water (very little for a better taste). To be honest, I wasn't expecting much--after all, it's just vitamin c, right? But after a long workout, I was feeling a little unwell, and usually that bode well. Took a packet, and...nothing. Wasn't expecting it to rejuvenate me right away, but it did combat any sickness that I was expecting the next day. I know my body well enough, and had I not taken Emergen-C, I would've felt some ill effect the next day. This is a great preventer. If you feel a cold coming on, or even suspect it because those around you are coughing, take a packet--you won't regret it. However, don't bother with it once you're already sick. I turned my mom onto this, and she loves it too, but she made the mistake of waiting after she felt sick to take it one time, and it was already too late at that point. They offer so many different flavors, but my favorite is still Super Orange or Tangerine. I wasn't too crazy about the Tropical flavor--it tasted a little off to me--but would love to try the Dragon Fruit flavor (even though Dragon Fruit really doesn't taste like anything). Tip: Dissolve 1 packet with very little water for a better taste, and keep away from the dust kickup when mixing so you don't inhale it.

column9: not as good tasting as it used to be

The only difference I found in the ingredients on the packages was that the old one listed malic acid, orange juice powder, natural flavors. column9: Have Mild-Medium Flu or Severe Cold... this stuff will have you back on your feet in no time.
column10: There have been 3 times in the past year when I have caught something severe enough from my child that she needed anti-biotics to kick it.  Due to not wanting to fool around with a 4 yr old's delecate immune system and consistent high fevers, once 3 days pass and she does not get better, I take her to her pediatrician.  Her doc does not like giving anti-biotics at all, but on 2 of the past 3 occasions when she has gotten severely sick, that's what she got.I don't have the luxury of just calling out of work at the drop of a hat to go see a doctor (those get reserved for my child) so that means when I catch something nasty, I've got to take supplements to kick it myself.If I take 3 of these packets per day for 3 days during a mild flu or severe cold, get at least 7 hrs of sleep and drink lots of water and tea, whatever I had is practically gone.  It eases my symptoms so at the most, I may take an ibuprofen or a couple of aspirin for a sore throat or muscles and that's it.I would say, if you are on prescription meds, an aspirin regiment or have some type of chronic disease (diabetes, heart disease, etc) that you are managing, taking 3 of these per day may be unwise if you are sick unless you get the go ahead from your doc.  If you are relatively healthy, not on prescription meds have a case of a mild - medium flu or severe cold... take a packet 3 times per day and feel yourself heal quickly.  My doc looked at the ingredients and said that me doing this would be fine (ask your doc to be sure).The standard vitamin c tablets don't seem to work for me as well, even in high doses, but this stuff taken when sick works wonders.

At 81 and having lost 1/2 of my household income because my hubby had a stroke one year ago and the rehab facility gets all of his income, I cannot afford to lose money on any product; thus I try to buy carefully. Even though this gruesome  vitamin was only $10.00, it can never be called a value for its money; given that you will likely have to throw the bottle away.I received it on May 21st and have been choking on it each morning. It was 100 tablets and that is a tremendous amount to discard but as soon as I find an easy to swallow replacement, this will be tossed. Until then, I must go through panic attacks every morning, fearing this is the time it will become jammed in my throat.It is too large and has little or no coating so that the minute it hits the tongue, the chalkiness starts adhering to the tongue and then no matter how much water you toss in your mouth, it won't easily go down.Worse yet, they are as hard as a brick and they are not scored, so cutting them in half is truly impossible. I have tried with a large sharp butcher knife, a large utility scissor and a serrated blade with which to score it myself. It cannot be cut in half.I will admit that I had esophageal cancer surgery in March so must be very careful in what I try to swallow but even had I had no surgery, I would have been unable to swallow these easily.Shame on these companies who see fit to make large, hard pills. There is little doubt it is not  necessary and then they do not warn you. I think all pills, capsules and tablets that cannot be seen should put the size under description. It is easy to do and would save the customer money and trouble. But, of course, that is likely why they do not. They would lose sales.

column9: Right after reading manufacturer's warning, I ended up at doctor's office
column10: From the manufacturer's link on the box you can find an impressive overview of the product. I had already taken 2 of the capsules while reviewing the link. It was too late when I came across the product's warning: "Caution: As with any dietary supplement, consult your healthcare practitioner before using this product, especially if you are pregnant, nursing, anticipate surgery, take medication on a regular basis or are otherwise under medical supervision." I take a very low dose of a blood pressure medication daily under bi-annual medical supervision from a doctor. In a panic I stood up and screamed out,  "What have I done?"With my heart racing, I called my doctor's office and they were able to work me in on what they said was a very busy day. I got to his office in less than 10 minutes using my emergency flashers and running red lights after first stopping and looking left, right, left for any oncoming traffic. The office receptionist saw me right away upon my arrival, but I had to wait and wait and wait. It was as if they didn't understand the caution from the manufacturer and what I did.  I paced back and forth in the waiting room, asking the front desk person how much longer every 5 minutes. I finally persuaded them to take me in front of a kid with the 103 fever (all he needed was some Tylenol).I showed the doctor the bottle from the "Garden of Life Vitamin C" and the manufacturer's caution I was able to pull-up on my phone. He asked me what else I had to eat or drink that day and I told him nothing. He appeared to study me while gently nodding his head up and down. It took him less than a minute to come up with a life saving solution for my irresponsible actions. He told me to put on an examination gown and then not to move, he would be right back. I ask him if he was going to get equipment to pump my stomach and he said, "Don't worry, I will take care of you."Ten minutes of what felt like an eternity had gone by and still no stomach pump. The interaction time with the vitamin C was increasing by every single second. Didn't he understand they just don't put warning precautions on labels for nothing. I jumped up to go find him and nicely remind him every single second counts in the 'Golden Hour'. I opened the exam room door and to my shock and horror he was standing outside of the exam room with 2 paramedics who had a stretcher. I was worse than I thought! The doctor so Kindly reassured me I was going to be alright, though. The paramedics were very nice as well, making sure I was very firmly secured to the stretcher so my arms wouldn't fall out in transit. I felt like I could breathe again, until the paramedics refused to put on the lights and siren to get me to the hospital stat.I was admitted to the hospital for observation, but there was no need to pump my stomach or start any kind of a chelation treatment on me. I believe they were concerned that my low dose of blood pressure medicine and the Garden of Life Vitamin C may have harmed my brain. They sent in what they called brain specialists to run a battery of tests on me using what seemed like just questions about everyday life. And no, I do not wet the bed! I am a grown man. After about 55 minutes of talking back and forth, the nice young doctors left and told me they were going to talk to the attending doctor. I took a deep swallow and ask them if I was going to be able to make it? They apparently didn't understand what I was asking when they answered yes. For the next three weeks I spent my days making little bird houses and other interesting things in what they called the arts and crafts room. The good things is I survived and lived to warn others of the potential dangers of mixing an all natural source of vitamin C with no GMOs, with a low dose of a blood pressure medicine. Now though, I have new meds to take in response to my vitamin C and BP med interaction and, I will have to be on them the rest of my life. I am just glad I lived through my ordeal and am able to warn others.

column9: "Isolates from food" can't fool my body.
column10: I emailed Garden of Life about the strange wording on the package. This is their detailed explanation:"Thank you for your email and interest in Garden of Life's products. This is to confirm that there is no ascorbic acid in our VC RAW Vitamin C. The Vitamins and Minerals that are in our Vitamin Code Products are in a whole-food form made with RAW Food-Created Nutrients. This process utilizes a single isolated vitamin or mineral (from food) that is fed to the yeast or probiotic. A specific peptide designed for that particular nutrient is then introduced in order to allow the nutrient to be metabolized (or absorbed) through the yeast's cell wall. This process mimics nature, just like when a plant takes an inorganic mineral salt that is naturally occurring in the soil (selenium for example), and absorbs it into its roots, the plant becomes rich in selenium. This process is conducted with two distinct organisms - S. cerevisiae (baker's yeast) and L. bulgaricus (probiotic culture used in traditional yogurt recipes which is non-dairy).Cultivated with their unique Code Factors intact, the RAW Food-Created Nutrients in Vitamin Code formulas enable natural recognition of nutrients by your body, just as nature intended. Code Factors are the known and yet to be discovered synergistic compounds found in food and are necessary for proper nutrient delivery. Providing these Code Factors infuses the essential elements of whole-foods that the body thrives upon.The Vitamin C is not coming from the Fruit and Vegetable Blend. That blend is added as a base to put the nutrients in to prevent us from using artificial fillers and binders."Hope this helps. You have to read it carefully to see the meandering around the word "synthetic." And note that there is no mention of "created enzymes" that would tell our body what these vitamins are.  I highly doubt that this process makes any enzymes like tyrosinase at the centre of the vitamin C molecule.  I do find I get a good circulation effect with better colour to my face with about 8 capsules dumped in my water with lysine/proline. Real or synthetic C will do this by increasing oxygen.  But I also noticed nails splitting and chipping after a few days, which indicates minerals being leached (as synthetic C is a known chelator).  The nails returned to normal when I stopped the "Raw C" and switched to camu camu powder. I am also waiting for Megafood Daily C Protect to arrive.  It's from oranges, not synthetic "isolates" like GOL vitamin code.  They stated in their email the vitamins are "isolates from food."  But GMO corn and tapioca are "food" and synthetic C is derived from them. FYI, a retired army flight surgeon has urged the CDC to study high dose vitamin C for Ebola because the disease is very similar to advanced scurvy.* Ebola Article by WM Wassell, MD"In summary, people taking 10+g vitamin C orally should be protected from Ebola. Those that get the disease should be cured quickly with IVC 50g/day for at least 3 days. Ebola depletes your vitamin C causing acute scurvy which kills you."-from vitamincfoundation.org

column9: Love Gaden of Life - Bad Supplier
column10: Love Gaden of Life - Bad Supplier3 weeks late and delivered in the heat and humidity of South Florida summer - NOT packed in dry ice like GoL recommends.  Will go to my local nutrition store and pay more...I trust them.  To start, RAW Probiotics are grown in a state-of-the-art culturing facility. When the probiotics are fully grown, they are quickly put into frozen storage.  They are then packed in dry ice and shipped overnight in refrigerated trucks to our manufacturing plant, where they are immediately transferred to our own freezers for storage until they are ready to be blended and encapsulated. The facility we use is exclusively dedicated to the production of our probiotics. That means that Garden of Life controls the environmental conditions—keeping it cold and at the proper humidity.  After blending and encapsulating, the RAW Probiotics are immediately moved back into cold storage.  When retailers order Raw Probiotics, the finished goods are picked and placed into special insulated containers, along with desiccants (moisture absorbing agents) and frozen packs so that they remain at optimal temperature and relative humidity all the way to our retail partners.  Retailers are instructed to store the RAW Probiotics in refrigeration until the consumer purchases them and the instructions on the packaging inform the consumer the product is best when refrigerated. With Garden of Life's Arrive Alive system, you can feel sure that you are getting what the label promises.

column9: like "New Chapter Activated C Food Complex
column10: This is Ascorbic Acid.They are tricky about the wording, but make no mistake: it is, of course, physically impossible to get 300mg of Vitamin C out of 20mg "RAW fruit and vegetable blend", or out of 100mg "RAW probiotic and enzyme blend".This company, like "New Chapter Activated C Food Complex, 180 Tablets", is preying on your lack of knowledge regarding vitamin labeling.They can say "Vitamin C" without explaining the source or type, because for label purposes, Vitamin C by default is ascorbic acid.The "RAW, Whole Food" part of the formula is the measly (worthless, really) 20mg fruit and vegetables. For reference, 20mg would fit on a pencil eraser.Unless the product says "Vitamin C (from berries)" or similar, than it is just plain old corn based ascorbic acid.Notice the only people saying it is not ascorbic acid are reviewers? The company will never state that on the box, on its website, or in an email, because it would be illegal to make a false claim.If you want natural Vitamin C, look for one from berries or at least a non-GMO, non-chinese corn source.

column9: Best Vitamin C I have found!
column10: Vitamin C is an amazing vitamin.  Not only will high quantities of Vitamin C help the body fight colds and other illnesses, but it improves allergies.  When we kept bees, we learned a mega dose of Vitamin C would eliminate the swelling associated with bee stings or prevent swelling all together if taken right away.  Our bodies cannot manufacture Vitamin C.  We must get it from food or supplements.  From my reading about Vitamin C, we probably need much more than most people get.  The government recommendations are only based on what it takes to prevent scurvy rather than what it takes to be healthy in general.  These days the soil on most farms is so depleted that it is pretty much impossible to get the nutrition we need from food alone so supplements are a necessity for good health. column10: I generally take ten 1000mg tablets spread over the course of the day. Taking ten at once would NOT be a good idea. Vitamin C leaves the system in a matter of hours so if you want the best results you need to take a couple at a time, a few hours apart. I've been taking large doses of vitamin C for the past 17 years. Maybe just luck but I haven't had even a common cold for over 17 years. I am not suggesting vitamin C will cure any existing condition other than scurvy. This terrible condition is a direct result of vitamin C deficiency. It takes very little vitamin C to prevent scurvy and most people get enough in their diet for that. I am a strong believer that larger than recommended doses of vitamin C can and does strengthen the immune system. I don't think any particular brand is superior to another. I chose this brand for the low price. I have not been disappointed.

Wow, I didn't realize how many are in this bottle until I saw it. There really is six months worth of caplets here (if you take one a day).  And only one per day is needed...the 1,000mg provides 1,667% Daily Value. Fortunately, Vitamin C is excreted by the kidneys so any extra that's in your body is just eliminated. You will find that the caplets are a little on the bigger side, but they have a vegetable coating so I've found they don't get stuck in my throat when I swallow them. It is also wise to take them with food though, as the ascorbic acid may cause burning in your stomach.There is one review saying that these are not gluten free. I understand the concern, because so many people now are allegeric or sensitive to them. I researched it, and all of the ingredients in question (the fillers that make up the bulk of the caplets...everything except the ascorbic acid) MAY START OUT as a corn or wheat product, but the compounds that are extracted no longer contain gluten. I have that same concern and have been taking them for a few months now, without any adverse affects.These are definitely a great value (the best I've seen on Amazon), especially if you use the Subscribe and Save. I'll certainly purchase these again when I'm running low.The last thing I'd like to say about these is how I've felt since taking them. There was once when I felt a cold and a sore throat coming on. In combination with a zinc supplement it never progressed to the full blown stage. Actually, I've been taking both for several years now and haven't caught a cold or the flu (I also take precautions while I'm in public (I  wash my hands or use hand sanitizer after coming out of a store, other public space or a restroom.
